\section{Introduction}
Hedge fund activism has become a significant phenomenon in recent years.
This kind of activism differs from more traditional forms of shareholder activism, such as shareholder proposals filed under SEC Rule 14a-8, both in the nature of the activists, as well as in the scale and type of intervention.\footnote{More traditional activism has often been initiated by pension funds and individual activists (sometimes called ``gadflies'') with relatively weaker incentives to generate higher returns by influencing the management of a firm.}
In contrast to more traditional activists, hedge funds have stronger incentives to produce higher returns, fewer conflicts of interest, and ``much more flexibility to intervene in the invested companies'' \citep[187]{Brav:2010gx}.
These differences appear to have led to hedge fund activists making a broader range of demands and adopting a wider range of tactics to have those demands met than traditional shareholder activists.

One tactic used by hedge fund activists is getting seats on boards of target companies for directors either formally affiliated with the activist or nominated by the activist (we refer to these directors collectively as ``activist directors'').
However, appointment of activist directors is unlikely to be costless to the activist.
First, there are direct costs of getting board representation, which \citet{Gantchev:2012wn} finds to be significant.
Second, by joining the board, the activists and activist directors stake their reputations on the future performance of the firm.
Third, board positions also come with fiduciary responsibilities towards all shareholders and may limit the ability of the activist to trade in the stock of the target when in possession of inside information.

Given the additional costs and commitment required of activists that get board representation, the existence of activist directors suggests that there are countervailing benefits.
Prior research provides limited insight into the nature of these benefits.\footnote{\citet{Coffee:2018} suggests that one benefit of board representation is access to insider information that can be traded on, though such trading would be illegal in many circumstances.}
\citet{Bebchuk:2017} speculate that ``introducing individuals into the boardroom who are sympathetic or at least open to the changes sought by the activist is an intermediary step that often facilitates such changes.''
However, given that activist directors rarely represent a majority of directors, they would still need to persuade other directors of the merits of any course of action suggested by activists and it is unclear why being in the board room is necessary to make their case.
One possibility is that the optimal set of actions is not observable without access to private information.
By gaining board representation, the activist director is able to provide advice that is contingent on a richer information set.
Given the lack of strong theoretical predictions on the reasons for activists to seek board representation, studying the actions of firms with activist directors provides new insight into these reasons, and also the effects of hedge fund activists.

Our paper addresses a number of questions related to activist directors.
First, we focus on the circumstances surrounding the appointment of activist directors to the board.
When do activists seek board representation and when are they successful in obtaining it?
Also, we closely examine the characteristics of activist directors.
How are the activist directors different from other directors?
How much support do they get from shareholders and what is their future career consequence like?
Furthermore, we examine the consequences of having an activist director on the board.
What impact do activists have on the target firms when they get on the board?
Does their impact differ from that of other activism cases?

Our sample of \Sexpr{num_events} activism events comprises all activism events targeted at US companies from 2004 to 2016.\footnote{We additionally require that the target firm is matched to CRSP, is not an investment trust or mutual fund, and that the event is not a control contest involving another corporation.}
In each case, we code whether the activist made demands for board representation and whether the activist obtained seats on the board.
We identify \Sexpr{prettyNum(dirs$all_dirs, big.mark=",")} directors who were appointed to the board either through proxy fights or in response to activist demands.
With regard to the first set of questions, we find, consistent with prior research, that activists tend to target firms with worse recent stock performance and ``value'' firms (i.e., those with low market-to-book ratios).
Conditional on being targeted by activists, we also find that activists are more likely to demand or get board representation when the firm has more institutional ownership, smaller market capitalization, worse stock market performance, and especially lower dividend payout levels.

We describe the characteristics of activist directors and find that activist director characteristics differ from new directors appointed at other firms, especially for the directors affiliated with activists.\footnote{\citet*{Gow:2014vf} show that activism is often associated with departure of incumbent directors.}
About \Sexpr{percent_aff} percent (\Sexpr{dirs$affiliated} of \Sexpr{dirs$all_dirs}) of activist directors are directly employed at the hedge fund activist; the rest (\Sexpr{dirs$unaffiliated}), while sponsored or supported by the activist, appear not to be affiliated with the activist.
Activist-affiliated directors (i.e., employees or principals of members of the activist group) are about 9 years younger than other activist directors and are much more likely to have the finance and accounting skill and much less frequently female than unaffiliated activist directors, who are less frequently female than new directors in general.
